NAME
	line-plot (display) - graph every numeric column of a history-style file as an anti-aliased auto-scaled series

INTERFACE
	display (MatrixDisplay)

READS
	<mount>		one sample per line: [ts] v1 [v2 ...] — an
			optional leading timestamp column followed by one
			or more numeric value columns, oldest first.

WRITES
	none (renders only)

DESCRIPTION
	The generic "graph this file" view.  Each value column becomes
	one polyline rendered through aadraw (analytic-coverage
	anti-aliasing), coloured from a fixed palette (theme accent,
	cyan, green, amber, text).  All series share one auto-scaled
	range whose min/max are labelled at the plot corners; a grid
	line marks zero when the range crosses it.  When a line has two
	or more columns the first is treated as a timestamp and dropped
	(the sysmon and llm-recorder history-ring convention); a
	single-column file plots as-is.  The title is the last two path
	components of the mount.  The file is re-read on every update
	tick and redrawn only when its contents change, so pointing it
	at a live ring (e.g. sysmon-svc's cpu/history) yields a moving
	chart — but any file an agent appends to with echo has the same
	shape.

SEE ALSO
	sparkline (the minimal one-line variant)
	sysmon-svc, llm-recorder (produce history rings this can graph)
